<div align="Center"><b><big><big>Bessel Functions</big></big></b></div>
 <br>
 Friedrich Wilhelm &nbsp; <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a> was a German astronomer and mathematician,best known for making
the first accurate measurement of the distance to astar.&nbsp; He established
the uniform system for computing star positions that is still in use.&nbsp;
In the investigation of problems connected with planetary perturbation, he
introduced into mathematics the &nbsp; <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a> functions as the solutionsof certain differential equations. The
functions are of great importancein determining the distribution and flow
of heat or electricity through acircular cylinder and in the solution ofproblems
concerning wave theory,elasticity, and hydrodynamics.<br>
<br>
<div align="Left">
<div align="Center">&nbsp; <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a>'s differential equation is as follows:<br>
</div>
<br>
<div align="Center">
<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" border="1" width="37%" bgcolor="#ccccff">
  <tbody>
    <tr valign="Top">
      <td valign="Top">                                                
      <div align="Center"><b>&nbsp; (d<sup>2</sup>u)/(dz<sup>2</sup>) + (1)/(z)
* (du)/(dz) + (1 - (s<sup>2</sup>/z<sup>2</sup>))u=0.</b> &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>(1)</b><br>
      </div>
      </td>
    </tr>
                
  </tbody>
</table>
<div align="Left"><br>
The <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a> function can be defined as a particular solutionof <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a>'s differential equation (1), with the exponent alpha =+s and with
the leading coefficient a<sub>0</sub>=[2<sup>s</sup>G(s+1)]<sup>-1</sup>.
&nbsp; Here, G is used to denote the gamma function (See <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Gauss.html">
Gauss</a> below for informationon the gamma function).&nbsp; Using the properties
of the gammafunction,weget <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a>'s function to be:<br>
<br>
<div align="Center">
<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" border="1" width="37%" bgcolor="#ccccff">
  <tbody>
    <tr valign="Top">
      <td valign="Top">                                                
      <div align="Center"><b>J<sub>s</sub>(z) = </b> <b>Sigma ((-1)<sup>j</sup>
)/(G(j+1)G(j+s+1))*(z/2)<sup>2j+s</sup>. &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
(2)</b></div>
      </td>
    </tr>
                
  </tbody>
</table>
<br>
<div align="Left">The sum of this series is a solution to (1) for any real
s except if s is a negative integer.&nbsp; If s is a negative integer, the
series is not defined.&nbsp; This is because G(s) is infinite for negative
integers s.&nbsp; For a given value of s, not an integer, the functions J<sub>
s</sub>(z) and J<sub>-s</sub>(z) give a pair of linearly independent solutions
of (1).&nbsp; Thus, all solutions of (1) are AJ<sub>s</sub>(z)+BJ<sub>-s</sub>
(z), for arbitrary constants A and B.&nbsp; It is important to note, however,
that&nbsp; J<sub>-s</sub>(z) is infinite at z=0.<br>
There are also identities that relate the <a href="http://www-groups.dcs.st-and.ac.uk/~history/Mathematicians/Bessel.html">
Bessel</a> functions for differentvaluesof s.&nbsp; They are as follows:<br>
<br>
<div align="Center">
<table cellpadding="2" cellspacing="2" border="1" width="50%" bgcolor="#ccccff">
  <tbody>
    <tr valign="Top">
      <td valign="Top">                                                
      <div align="Left"><b> &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; J<sub>s+/-1</sub>(z)=(s/z)J<sub>s</sub>
(z)-/+J'(z). &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (3)</b><br>
      </div>
      </td>
    </tr>
    <tr valign="Top">
      <td valign="Top"><b> &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; J<sub>s-1</sub>(z) + J<sub>s+1</sub>(z)
=(2s/z)J<sub>s</sub>(z).</b> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <b>(4)</b><br>
      </td>
    </tr>
                
  </tbody>
</table>
<br>
<div align="Left">The first pair of these recursion relations (3) follows
from the series expansion (2), while (4) follows from (3). &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;
&nbsp; &nbsp; <br>
<br>
</div>
